Here's the recommended approach using **Window lifecycle events** and `Preferences`:

### 1. Create a custom `Window` subclass

```csharp
// AppWindow.cs
public class AppWindow : Window
{
    public AppWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        if (Page is AppShell shell &&
            shell.CurrentPage?.BindingContext is NoteViewModel vm)
        {
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", vm.DraftText);
        }
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        if (Page is AppShell shell &&
            shell.CurrentPage?.BindingContext is NoteViewModel vm)
        {
            vm.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
        }
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
        if (Page is AppShell shell &&
            shell.CurrentPage?.BindingContext is NoteViewModel vm)
        {
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", vm.DraftText);
        }
    }
}
```

### 2. Return it from `App.CreateWindow`

```csharp
// App.xaml.cs
public partial class App : Application
{
    public App()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
    }

    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new AppShell());
}
```

### 3. Clear the draft when the user explicitly saves

```csharp
// In your save command handler
Preferences.Remove("draft_text");
```

### Key points

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| **Save in both `OnStopped` and `OnDestroying`** | Android's back button can skip `Stopped` and go straight to `Destroying` |
| **Use `Preferences` not a database** | Lifecycle handlers must complete in ~1–2 s to avoid ANR / watchdog kills |
| **Don't use `OnResumed` for first launch** | `Resumed` only fires after `Stopped`. The initial sequence is `Created → Activated` |

If you need to restore the draft on a **cold start** too (app was killed), read `Preferences` in your ViewModel constructor:

```csharp
public NoteViewModel()
{
    DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
}
```
